$","h2",null,{"className":"mb-4 text-[20px] font-semibold text-primary","children":"What it is"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-4 text-[15px] leading-[1.75] text-secondary","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":"A two-player reaction time game on a custom-designed PCB. A white LED lights up at a random interval, and whoever presses their button first wins. The winner's color LED lights up. A buzzer sounds. Reset and go again."}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The point wasn't the game. The point was going from schematic to physical board — learning KiCad, laying out traces, sending Gerbers to a fab, and soldering it by hand."}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"mb-4 text-[20px] font-semibold text-primary","children":"How it was built"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-6 text-[15px] leading-[1.75] text-secondary","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"relative aspect-video w-full overflow-hidden rounded-[10px]","children":["$","$L3",null,{"src":"/images/reaction-game/pcb-schematic.png","alt":"KiCad schematic showing Arduino Uno, five LEDs with resistors, buzzer, and two push buttons","fill":true,"className":"object-contain bg-white"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"relative aspect-video w-full overflow-hidden rounded-[10px]","children":["$","$L3",null,{"src":"/images/reaction-game/pcb-layout.png","alt":"KiCad PCB layout view showing component footprints, copper traces, and pad placements","fill":true,"className":"object-contain bg-white"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"-mt-2 font-mono text-[12px] text-muted","children":"PCB layout — KiCad"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"Designed entirely in KiCad. The schematic has an Arduino Uno, five LEDs with current-limiting resistors, a buzzer, and two push buttons. Once the schematic was right, I laid out the PCB. I placed components, routed traces, and set clearances, then sent the Gerber files to JLCPCB for fabrication."}],["$","div",null,{"className":"flex flex-co